## What the Capstone Is — and What It Is Not

Day 85 completed the governance foundations section — risk communication, stakeholder communication scenarios, and the annual authorization recommendation as the most consequential communication the ISSO produces. Days 69 through 85 covered the Monitor step, system disposal, policy writing, AWS automation tooling, POA&M management, compliance checklists, audit readiness, incident response, third-party risk, metrics design, dashboard visualization, and stakeholder communication. That is seventeen days of governance foundations on top of sixty-eight days of RMF execution.

Day 86 begins the capstone. I want to be direct about what this capstone is, because understanding that will shape how I approach the next twelve days.

This capstone is not a fresh GRC plan built from scratch. I have spent 85 days building a deeply detailed GRC program for a specific system — OpenMRS on AWS for a healthcare NGO called MyClinic. Every component a GRC program needs has been developed in operational depth: the FIPS 199 categorization, the full control selection and implementation, the formal assessment, the conditional ATO, the authorization conditions, the continuous monitoring program, the POA&M management, the policies, the incident response playbooks, the metrics framework, the communication protocols. The SSP has been through six version updates. The POA&M has cycled through 12 items and 5 closures. The system has been through a full quarter of post-authorization monitoring.

The capstone's purpose is synthesis — taking everything developed across 85 days and organizing it into a coherent, navigable GRC program document that demonstrates what a complete security program looks like when all the components are integrated. This is the document that a successor ISSO, an external assessor, or a new organizational leader should be able to read to understand the full security posture of the OpenMRS system.

This distinction matters because it changes the approach. I am not designing a new program. I am documenting, organizing, and connecting the program that has been developed in operational detail throughout this project — and thinking carefully about what the integrated view reveals that the day-by-day development did not.

