## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the capstone structure today is understanding the difference between a GRC program document and a GRC activity log.

An activity log records what was done: Day 33 produced an asset inventory, Day 38 produced a risk register, Day 52 produced a continuous monitoring strategy. A complete and accurate activity log is useful for reference — any individual day's work can be found and reviewed.

A GRC program document tells a coherent story about how the security program works: what the system is, what risks it faces, what controls address those risks, how those controls are maintained over time, and what the organizational accountability structure looks like. The program document connects the components — showing how the risk register informs the control selection, how the control selection informs the SSP, how the SSP informs the assessment, how the assessment informs the POA&M, and how the POA&M informs the continuous monitoring program.

The connections between components are what the capstone adds. Eighty-five days of daily entries developed each component in depth. The capstone demonstrates that they form a system, not a collection of documents.

