## The Integration Question — What Does the Whole Reveal?

Looking at all nine sections together, one integration insight stands out that individual sections would not reveal:

The OpenMRS security program is stronger at technical control implementation and weaker at administrative process consistency. The technical controls — encryption, MFA enforcement, network segmentation, automated monitoring — have functioned reliably throughout the authorization period. The administrative processes — CM-3 change management compliance, AT-2 training calendar discipline, HR-to-ISSO role change notification — have required repeated remediation because the organizational culture has not yet fully integrated security process compliance as a routine expectation rather than an IT team concern.

This pattern — strong technical controls, developing administrative discipline — is characteristic of organizations early in their security program maturity. It is not a failure. It is a stage. The second authorization year's primary development opportunity is not adding more technical controls but strengthening the organizational processes that make the technical controls' benefit sustainable over time.

The capstone's honest articulation of this pattern — supported by the specific evidence of the M-002, A-7, and M-004 findings all involving process lapses rather than technical failures — is the most valuable insight the integrated view provides.

