## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The pattern of strong technical controls alongside underdeveloped administrative processes is directly illustrated by the **2015 Anthem Health breach** — the largest healthcare data breach on record at the time, affecting approximately 78.8 million individuals.

The OCR investigation and post-breach analysis found that Anthem had invested significantly in technical security infrastructure. The breach was enabled not by a failure of the technical controls but by a spear-phishing attack that compromised an administrator's credentials — the technical controls that existed were not sufficient to detect or prevent the breach because the administrative security awareness program had not produced the behavioral change needed to resist targeted phishing.

The OCR settlement ($16 million) and the post-breach analysis identified security awareness training as a significant program gap — the human layer had not received the same investment as the technical layer.

For the OpenMRS capstone, the Anthem pattern is the honest context for understanding why the phishing simulation program is not just a nice-to-have metric improvement but a genuine second-year security program priority. The technical controls protect against opportunistic attacks. Behavioral security awareness protects against the targeted attacks — like the phishing campaigns the HC3 briefing identified as elevated for organizations matching MyClinic's profile — where the attacker's goal is to compromise legitimate credentials and use them through the technical controls rather than around them.

